Hi everyone,

In my problem, I want to implement the exponentiated gradient update as in Kivinen & Warmuth (1997).
(Kivinen, Jyrki and Warmuth, Manfred K. Exponentiated gradient versus gradient descent for linear predictors. Information and Computation, 132(1):1–63, 1997)

I would like to utilise the current implementation of logsumexp during SGD training in which I apply to computation of parameters/gradients. 
The update formula of EG is defined as y_{t+1} := 1/Z * y_t * exp(-eta * dL(y_t)) where Z = \sum_i y_{t,i} * exp(-eta * dL(y_{t,i})).
To avoid the underflow/overflow issues, I take the log of y_{t+1}, resulting in: log(y_{t+1}) = log(y_t) - eta * dL(y_t) - logZ.
Here, logZ refers to logsumexp.

Assume that I have new SGD trainer denoted as EGTrainer having the update_rule_dev function implemented as follows:
```
template <class MyDevice>
void EGTrainer::update_rule_dev(const MyDevice & dev, real scale, real gscale, const std::vector<Tensor*> & ts) {
  //------------------------------------------------------------------
  // Add momentum
  ts[2]->tvec().device(*dev.edevice) = ts[2]->tvec() * momentum - ts[1]->tvec() * (eta * scale * gscale);
  //------------------------------------------------------------------

  //------------------------------------------------------------------
  // METHOD 2: advanced implementation (supposedly faster)
  ts[0]->tvec().device(*dev.edevice) = ts[0]->tvec().log() + ts[2]->tvec() / model->weight_decay.current_weight_decay();// with momentum

  float* aux_mem = 0;// how to set this?

  Tensor z(Dim({1}, 1), (float*)aux_mem, ts[0]->device, DeviceMempool::FXS);
  Tensor m(Dim({1}, 1), (float*)aux_mem + z.d.size(), ts[0]->device, DeviceMempool::FXS);

  logsumexp(dev, *ts[0], m, z);

  ts[0]->tvec().device(*dev.edevice) = (ts[0]->tvec() - as_scalar(z)).exp();
  //------------------------------------------------------------------
}
```

I am confused with the followings:
1) Are the dims of z and m correct?
2) How to set aux_mem for initialising the tensors z and m?
3) is DeviceMempool::FXS correct?

I appreciate if someone can help on this!

Thank you very much!

--
Vu

I was recently trying to come up with a way to apply a feature to some scripts but not others, essentially ignoring language, but couldn't think of a good way to do so with feature syntax. I've found that just the following source:

```
feature liga {
    script latn;
    sub f i by fi;
} liga;
```

doesn't even seem to exclude the "fi" ligatures from non-latn scripts. For example, testing output with harfbuzz:

```
$ hb-shape --script=arab out.otf "afib"
[b=3+1150|fi=1+1135|a=0+1114]
```

Another issue is that the following source:

```
feature locl {
    script latn;
    language FRA;
    sub [uni2009] by [uni2009.fra];
} locl;

feature liga {
   script latn;
   sub f i by fi;
} liga;
```

excludes the "fi" ligation from French, since a languagesystem is made for latn/FRA to include uni2009 -> uni2009.fra but the ligation is only included in the latn/dftl languagesystem.

So basically I'm wondering a) why my first example happens at all, and b) how I can achieve per-script inclusion of substitution features.

In the [OpenType Feature File Specification](http://www.adobe.com/devnet/opentype/afdko/topic_feature_file_syntax.html), example 1 of section 6.h.ii. “Specifying Contextual Positioning with explicit lookup references” seems syntactically malformed:
```
lookup CNTXT_PAIR_POS {
     position T o -10;
     position T c by -12;
} CNTXT_PAIR_POS;
 
lookup CNTXT_MARK_TO_BASE {
     position base o 
     position base c 
} CNTXT_MARK_TO_BASE;
 
feature test {
     substitute T' lookup CNTXT_PAIR_POS [o c]' @ALL_MARKS' lookup CNTXT_MARK_TO_BASE;
} test;
```

Would it be possible to fix the specification, so that the example is syntactically correct?

