@Caoimhinmg I am using cit_magic.py to convert some data files from Scott Bogue at Occidental College and I am a bit confused by the weight/vol moment to magnetization conversion code.

First, the help says the volume/weight can be set to gm, kg, cc, or m3, but only cc or m3 are used in the following code (if not cc or m3, defaults to cc). I'll remove the weight options in the help decription for now.

Then there is this code:
if vol!=1.0:
            if norm=='cc':units="1"
            if norm=='m3':units="2"
            SpecRec['weight']=""
            if units=="1" or "":
                SpecRec['volume']='%10.3e'%(vol*1e-6)
            else:
                SpecRec['volume']='%10.3e'%(vol)
        else:
            if norm=='cc':units="1"
            if norm=='m3':units="2"
            SpecRec['volume']=""
            if units=="1" or "":
                SpecRec['weight']='%10.3e'%(vol*1e-3)
            else:
                SpecRec['weight']='%10.3e'%(vol)

I'm not sure why the "norm" variable is converted to "units" variable, but mainly I'm not familiar with the Berkeley convention of if the vol is set to 1.0 then use normalization by weight instead (but still using the volume info in the conversion).

Also conversion from cc (cm3) to m3 should be a factor of (1/100)^3 = 1e-6.

Bogue uses 1.0 in the volume to indicate volume not given, but I still think in that case he would want the moment converted to some standard (2.5cm^3 would be good) volume.

Enlightenment on this issue would be appreciated. Thanks.

