When `error_already_set` is thrown by Python C++ API code inside the `PYBIND11_PLUGIN` macro block, the `std::exception` catch block defined by the macro somehow doesn't work, and the result is a `py::error_already_set` that propagates up and terminates the program, but with a *different* Python exception type and message than the original; regardless of what the original is, I always see:
```
terminate called after throwing an instance of 'pybind11::error_already_set'
  what():  SystemError: <built-in method __contains__ of dict object at 0x7ffff6bab480> returned a result with an error set
```

I haven't been able to figure out how this is happening, but it's easily fixed by adding an extra
```
try {
    ...
} catch (pybind11::error_already_set & err) {
    err.restore();
    return nullptr;
}
```
around the offending code.  My best guess is that the `error_already_set` destructor is causing another instance of `py::error_already_set` to be raised somehow, but that too seems impossible.

In any case, my recommendation is that we add an explicit catch block for `error_already_set` to the `PYBIND11_PLUGIN` macro that simply uses that exception rather than raising `ImportError` (or at least uses the original error message).  That will make it much easier to diagnose failing code.

Here's a complete example to reproduce the problem:
```
#include "pybind11/pybind11.h"

PYBIND11_PLUGIN(import_abort) {
