In an embedded python application, I would like to create a python binding to interact with a C++ object that was already created (typically a singleton). The scenario is something like follows:

```
struct Dog {
    void bark() { printf("Bark!\n"); }
};

int main()
{
  auto dog = new Dog;
  Py_Initialize();
  initexample();

  // TBD - Add binding  between dog and example.dog .

  PyRun_StringFlags("import example\n"
                               "\n"
                               "example,dog.bark()\n"  // Access the C++ allocated object dog.
                               , Py_file_input, main_dict, main_dict, NULL);
  Py_Finalize();
}
```

For this to work the python object `dog` either needs to be defined as a python module, or as a class with all its members being static. 

One solution would be to define the class `Dog` to be a singleton, and then create it once for C++ and then a second time (which will just return a pointer to the singleton) the python binding. But I wonder if there is any solution without changing the definition of Dog?

